For each problem, we will consider a set that is "large" enough, containing all objects under consideration.
Such a set is called a universal set and is usually denoted by U. In this case, all sets under consideration are
subsets of U and they can be written in the form {x € U: P(x)}.

Example In considering addition and subtraction of whole numbers (0, 1, 2, 3, 4, ...), we may use Z (the set of
all integers) as a universal set.
(1) The set of all positive even numbers can be written as {x € Z: x > 0 and x is divisible by 2).
(2) The set of all prime numbers can be written as {x € Z: x > 0 and x has exactly two divisors).
